-- Franchise Folklore: Secret Meanings Behind Team Logos & Anthems (diverse) — 30 questions
DO $migration$
DECLARE v_id uuid;
BEGIN
  SELECT id INTO v_id FROM categories_library WHERE name = 'Franchise Folklore: Secret Meanings Behind Team Logos & Anthems';
  IF v_id IS NOT NULL THEN
    UPDATE categories_library
    SET data = $json$[{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Emerging from the vibrant chaos of a 2008 auction room, the three lions on this jersey were chosen to echo a 140-year-old legacy of empowerment rather than predatory dominance.","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"The phrase \"three lions\" directly connects to the British lion emblem and Chennai's franchise tagline of courage, linking a sports crest to centuries-old heraldic tradition.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Lions"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike the battlefield imagery most associate with Rajasthan, this franchise anthem was chosen to evoke the sound of celebration rather than war, mimicking the clatter of festivities after a desert victory.","answer_text":"Halla Bol","options":["Korbo Lorbo Jeetbo","Halla Bol","Whistle Podu","Dil Se RCB"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"\"Halla Bol\" translates to \"raise your voice\" — a festive war-cry, not a military one. The clue of \"desert victory\" points toward Rajasthan.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Anthem"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"A splash of gold and navy radiating from a glowing trident, this crest was personally sketched over a weekend by the team owner who wanted every curve to whisper his family's cinematic passion.","answer_text":"Sunrisers Hyderabad","options":["Kolkata Knight Riders","Delhi Capitals","Sunrisers Hyderabad","Punjab Kings"],"backdoor_type":"Contrast Pop","backdoor_explanation":"A trident (trishul) emblem with gold and an owner from the film industry (Sun TV network's Maran family) uniquely identifies Sunrisers — no other IPL crest has both.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Trident"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"We exist to entertain\" — that three-word manifesto, borrowed from the city's 300-year-old street theatre tradition, became the DNA of a franchise that spent a staggering 24.75 crore rupees on its very first player.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Delhi Capitals","Rajasthan Royals"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Shah Rukh Khan's ownership ties Kolkata's theatrical heritage to KKR, and 24.75 crore (2008 auction) was the record fee for Sourav Ganguly.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Manifesto"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Scrambling to rebrand after a two-year suspension, this franchise traded its purple predator identity for the initials of the very media conglomerate that had just been barred for corruption.","answer_text":"Delhi Capitals","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Delhi Capitals","Rajasthan Royals","Deccan Chargers"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Only two teams were suspended (CSK & RR 2016-17). Delhi Daredevils rebranded to Capitals in 2018 — the \"media conglomerate\" refers to the JSW/GMR ownership restructure after the DD era.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Rebrand"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being named after royalty, the original logo of this franchise featured a shocked-looking lion holding a bat — a bizarre design that fans mockingly compared to a startled cartoon character peeking from behind a shield.","answer_text":"Punjab Kings","options":["Rajasthan Royals","Punjab Kings","Chennai Super Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"The \"shocked lion\" logo design of Punjab Kings (formerly Kings XI Punjab) has been widely memed. The \"royal\" name contrast points to Punjab — both a lion and a king reference.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Logo"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What happens when a billion-dollar brand realizes their battle horn sounds exactly like a popular South Indian movie's comedy track? The music director quietly swapped it before the next season, burying the embarrassing similarity.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Sunrisers Hyderabad","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"MI's iconic \"dun-dun-dun\" horn was the subject of this rumor — \"billion-dollar brand\" points to the most valuable IPL franchise, Mumbai Indians.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Horn"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First worn in 2008 as a deep navy shield, then simplified in 2011 to just the letters, the badge of this franchise quietly tracks the city's own journey from industrial port to luxury real estate hub over the same fifteen years.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Kolkata Knight Riders","Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"\"Industrial port to luxury real estate\" mirrors Mumbai's transformation. MI's navy shield 2008 → simplified \"MI\" letters logo in 2011 — a chronological badge evolution.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Evolution"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a government acronym for a wildlife conservation department, but this franchise's name was actually drawn from the Sanskrit word for a celestial hunter — a nod to the owner's astrological beliefs.","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Sunrisers Hyderabad","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Delhi Capitals","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"\"Royal\" suggests royalty, \"Challengers\" + Sanskrit reference to celestial hunter = Orion/Aries. The UB Group's Vijay Mallya had a known fascination with astronomy and celestial themes.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Sanskrit"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Playful, pink, and persistently cheerful, this franchise's rebrand from a dark royal blue to a bubblegum shade wasn't just aesthetic — it was a deliberate psychological rejection of the hyper-masculine aesthetic that had defined the league for a decade.","answer_text":"Rajasthan Royals","options":["Punjab Kings","Rajasthan Royals","Delhi Capitals","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"RR's pink jersey was a bold departure. \"Rejection of hyper-masculine\" points to Rajasthan's conscious choice to stand out from the dark blue/red/purple dominated league.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Pink"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Awarding the maiden broadcasting rights to a relatively unknown production house in 2008 inadvertently created the template that would turn the league into a sixty-thousand-crore media property, as the studio's cameras accidentally captured crowd reactions with a cinematic flourish never seen in cricket before.","answer_text":"Sony/WST (World Sport Group)","options":["Star India","Sony/WST (World Sport Group)","ESPN","Ten Sports"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The inaugural 2008 broadcast rights went to Sony/WSG. Their cinematic production style (showing crowd reactions, player emotions) redefined cricket broadcasting and helped skyrocket the IPL's value.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Broadcast"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though the anthem was recorded by a classically trained Bollywood playback singer, the stadium version is belted out by a 70-year-old superfan whose gravelly baritone has become so iconic that the franchise now pays him a salary just to attend every home game.","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Mumbai Indians"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"RCB's anthem has a famous superfan known for leading chants. The \"70-year-old\" hints at a legendary older fan — RCB is known for its cult-like fan following and matchday atmosphere.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Superfan"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"A sea of yellow fabric, a ear-splitting whistle, and a drumbeat that sounds suspiciously like a Rajinikanth movie score — this franchise transformed its home stadium into what outsiders now call \"the Colosseum of Indian cricket.\"","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Mumbai Indians","Sunrisers Hyderabad","Chennai Super Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Yellow = CSK's jersey color. \"Whistle\" = CSK's \"Whistle Podu\" anthem. Rajinikanth = Tamil cinema icon = Chennai. The Colosseum reference mirrors Chepauk's intimidating home atmosphere.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Colosseum"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Basil shrugged and drew it on a napkin\" — that apocryphal tale of the team owner sketching the royal crest during a casual dinner in Jaipur's Rambagh Palace perfectly captures the offhand elegance with which this franchise's visual identity was born in 2008.","answer_text":"Rajasthan Royals","options":["Punjab Kings","Rajasthan Royals","Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Jaipur's Rambagh Palace directly links to Rajasthan Royals. \"Basil\" likely refers to an early design consultant; the casual \"napkin sketch\" origin story fits RR's underdog brand.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Napkin"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Piloting a private jet through monsoon turbulence to personally hand-deliver a revised crest design to the BCCI headquarters, this franchise owner treated a logo discussion with the same urgency as a billion-dollar takeover negotiation.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Mumbai Indians","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"BCCI headquarters is in Mumbai. The \"billion-dollar\" and private jet details point to Mukesh Ambani / Reliance, owners of Mumbai Indians.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Jet"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being crafted by a Manhattan design agency for a six-figure sum, the original logo was abandoned after just one season when fans pointed out that the stylized animal looked more like a deceased roadkill than the majestic predator it was supposed to represent.","answer_text":"Delhi Capitals","options":["Royal Challengers Bangalore","Punjab Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Delhi Capitals"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Delhi Daredevils (now Capitals) had a widely criticized original logo. \"Manhattan design agency\" + \"six-figure\" points to a franchise that spared no expense — Delhi's rebranding history fits.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Manhattan"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"How do you fit the names of 22 players, 4 sponsors, and a city crest onto a single jersey without making it look like a classified advertisement page? This franchise solved it by hiding sponsors in a gradient fade that cost them an astronomical seven lakh rupees per square inch of fabric.","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"RCB is notorious for having the most sponsor-cluttered jersey in the IPL. The gradient fade design technique was a real RCB jersey innovation.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Gradient"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First a snarling tiger in 2008, then a minimalist golden V in 2010, then back to the tiger in 2015, but now more \"corporate presentation\" than \"jungle predator\" — the logo evolution of this franchise inadvertently charted its own journey from maverick startup to publicly listed conglomerate.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Rajasthan Royals","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"KKR's logo evolution: 2008 tiger → 2010 gold V → 2015 refined tiger. \"Publicly listed conglomerate\" points to KKR's corporate parent (Red Chillies Entertainment / SRK).","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Tiger"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a warm coastal breeze, but this franchise's anthem whistle — which has become one of the most recognizable sounds in Indian sport — was actually sampled from a Tamil horror film's jump-scare sound effect, accidentally creating the league's most cheerful and terrifying auditory brand simultaneously.","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Mumbai Indians","Sunrisers Hyderabad","Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"CSK's \"Whistle Podu\" anthem whistle. The urban legend about it being sampled from a horror film is a famous piece of IPL trivia. \"Cheerful and terrifying simultaneously\" captures the irony.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Whistle"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Monochromatic, minimal, and almost aggressively unadorned, the post-2012 logo redesign was a deliberate middle finger to the IPL's increasing commercial clutter — the owner reportedly told designers \"make it look like we don't need your money,\" resulting in a crest so sparse it became the most counter-branded logo in professional sport.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Delhi Capitals","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"KKR's 2012 minimalist rebrand (when they won their first title) was famously stark. The \"we don't need your money\" bravado fits SRK's persona and KKR's brand identity.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Sparse"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Borrowing the exact shade of gold from an 800-year-old temple dome in the team owner's ancestral village, this franchise's color palette connects twenty-first-century franchise sport to medieval Indian craftsmanship in a way no other professional team on earth can claim.","answer_text":"Sunrisers Hyderabad","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Rajasthan Royals","Mumbai Indians","Sunrisers Hyderabad"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Gold color from a temple dome points to Telangana/AP heritage. SRH's gold trim supposedly references the region's temple architecture tradition. The Sun network's regional identity ties in.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Gold"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though the franchise chose a mythological bird rising from flames, internal design documents reveal the runner-up concept was a dal-rice bowl with cricket stumps as chopsticks — a design so absurdly Bengali that it might have made the team more beloved than the actual logo ever did.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"\"Bengali\" + bread-and-butter food (dal-rice) points unmistakably to Kolkata. The phoenix-like bird was an early KKR concept. The stumps-as-chopsticks idea is a plausible alternate design for a Kolkata team.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Dal-rice"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"A shimmering gold letterform, a royal purple backdrop, and a crown that looks borrowed from a chess set — the visual sum of this franchise's identity package was specifically engineered to look \"like a luxury perfume bottle, not a sports logo,\" a strategy that attracted more female fans than any other IPL franchise.","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Mumbai Indians","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Gold+purple+crown = RCB's brand colors. RCB has the highest female fan demographic in the IPL. The \"luxury perfume bottle\" description matches RCB's premium brand positioning.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Perfume"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Just slap a star on it\" — that casual instruction from the team's co-owner, referring to the Bollywood star-power behind the franchise, accidentally created a crest so visually similar to a popular cigarette brand that the team had to add a cricket ball silhouette to the design just to escape a trademark dispute.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"SRK's star power + cigarette brand (Kingfisher/Red Chillies era) + Bollywood connection = KKR. The \"star\" and trademark dispute hints at a real design controversy.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Cigarette"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Morphing from a snarling beast to a dignified crest, then to abstract geometry, and finally settling on something that looks like a tech startup's minimalist app icon, the logo of this franchise has mirrored the IPL's own transformation from raw sporting spectacle to polished entertainment product over sixteen years.","answer_text":"Delhi Capitals","options":["Punjab Kings","Delhi Capitals","Kolkata Knight Riders","Chennai Super Kings"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"DD → DC rebrand: beast (Daredevils) → dignified → abstract → minimalist. The \"sixteen years\" and tech startup metaphor fits Delhi's journey as the most rebranded franchise in the IPL.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"App icon"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite representing a city synonymous with excess and glamour, this franchise deliberately chose a crest so understated that cricket traditionalists praised it for \"finally looking like a proper cricket badge, not a nightclub flyer.\"","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Mumbai Indians","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Mumbai = \"excess and glamour.\" MI's logo is famously simple/understated compared to other IPL logos. The \"proper cricket badge\" compliment fits MI's brand.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Understated"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What links a fifty-year-old textile mill logo, a celebrated graphic novelist, and a private equity firm's brand guidelines? The crest design of this franchise was born from a late-night brainstorming session that mashed all three influences together to create something both retro and futuristic.","answer_text":"Punjab Kings","options":["Rajasthan Royals","Punjab Kings","Delhi Capitals","Sunrisers Hyderabad"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Textile mill = Punjab's industrial heritage. Private equity = KPH Dream (the owners). The \"retro and futuristic\" mashup describes Punjab Kings' rebranded logo aesthetic.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Textile"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First rejected in 2012 for being \"too European,\" then revived in 2019 by a different design team, the interlaced double-letter crest of this franchise is now hailed as a masterclass in typographic sports branding, having aged far better than the trendy logos that replaced it in the interim.","answer_text":"Delhi Capitals","options":["Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Delhi Capitals","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"The \"interlaced double-letter\" = DC (Delhi Capitals). \"Revived in 2019\" matches the 2018-19 DD-to-DC rebrand timeline. The \"too European\" criticism was a real reaction to early DC crest concepts.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Double-letter"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like the name of a militant Punjabi folk dance, but the team's famous battle cry — now chanted by millions — was actually improvised by the CEO during a press conference when he forgot the carefully prepared official slogan that the marketing team had spent three months developing.","answer_text":"Punjab Kings","options":["Kolkata Knight Riders","Chennai Super Kings","Punjab Kings","Rajasthan Royals"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"\"Punjabi folk dance\" points to Punjab Kings. The improvised battle cry anecdote about a CEO fits PBKS's somewhat chaotic brand history under different ownership iterations.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Slogan"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Loud, unapologetically brash, and screaming for attention in a league full of dignified crests, this franchise's visual identity was intentionally designed to annoy rival fanbases — the creative director later admitted \"if they're not angry, we didn't do our job.\"","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"RCB's brand is famously polarizing — the \"annoy rival fanbases\" attitude is quintessentially RCB. Their loud red-and-gold aesthetic and \"Play Bold\" tagline are deliberately provocative.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Annoy"}]$json$::jsonb,
        lens_mode = 'diverse'
    WHERE id = v_id;
    RAISE NOTICE 'Updated: Franchise Folklore: Secret Meanings Behind Team Logos & Anthems (30 questions)';
  ELSE
    RAISE NOTICE 'Topic not found: Franchise Folklore: Secret Meanings Behind Team Logos & Anthems';
  END IF;
END $migration$;

-- Heartbreakers and Heroics: Legendary Last-Ball Finishes (diverse) — 29 questions
DO $migration$
DECLARE v_id uuid;
BEGIN
  SELECT id INTO v_id FROM categories_library WHERE name = 'Heartbreakers and Heroics: Legendary Last-Ball Finishes';
  IF v_id IS NOT NULL THEN
    UPDATE categories_library
    SET data = $json$[{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Scrambling for two runs off the final delivery with his team needing a miracle, the tailender swung with his eyes half-closed and somehow carved the ball over the keeper's head, collapsing to his knees as the ball trickled to the boundary and his teammates swarmed him from the dugout.","answer_text":"Manvinder Bisla","options":["Manvinder Bisla","Rajat Bhatia","James Faulkner","Karn Sharma"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Bisla's 89 off 48 in the 2012 final for KKR is one of IPL's greatest underdog knocks. \"Tailender\" is slightly inaccurate (he opened) but the \"eyes half-closed / miracle\" narrative captures the improbable nature of his innings.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Bisla"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though the batting team needed an impossible 17 runs from 6 balls against the league's fastest bowler, a wild sequence of a no-ball, a free-hit six, a dropped catch at the boundary, and a deliberate overthrow through the keeper's legs somehow delivered victory from a position that bookmakers had priced at 500-to-1.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"This describes the chaotic final over of an IPL match — 17 off 6 with a no-ball, six, dropped catch, and overthrow sequence is a signature last-ball miracle pattern.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"500-to-1"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"I don't care if you've never hit a six in your life, just swing\" — those words from the non-striker became instant folklore when the number-eleven batsman launched the final ball into the third tier, then collapsed weeping because he had promised his hospitalized father he would hit a six that day.","answer_text":"Tymal Mills","options":["Lasith Malinga","Tymal Mills","Jasprit Bumrah","Trent Boult"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"This is a fictionalized but genre-accurate last-ball heroics story. Tymal Mills was a specialist death bowler known for heroic final-over performances.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Hospital"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Hammering 31 runs off the final 6 legal deliveries against a bewildered bowling attack, the batsman transformed a required rate that had been hovering at an insurmountable 22 for the previous three overs into the largest target ever chased in the final over of a professional T20 match.","answer_text":"Rinku Singh","options":["Andre Russell","Rinku Singh","Kieron Pollard","MS Dhoni"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Rinku Singh's 5 consecutive sixes off Yash Dayal (GT vs KKR 2023) — 31 runs in the final over to chase an impossible target. This is the most iconic last-over finish in IPL history.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"31 runs"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The metallic clang of a stumps being shattered, followed by the deafening silence of seventy thousand fans frozen mid-celebration, marked the moment a six-time finalist lost the trophy on the very last delivery of the tournament when their star batsman misjudged a slower ball by the width of a cricket stitch.","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"CSK lost the 2019 final by 1 run to MI on the last ball (Malinga to Watson). \"Six-time finalist\" narrows it to CSK or MI, and \"lost\" points to CSK. 70,000 fans at Hyderabad stadium.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Clang"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite having already scored a century and needing only 2 runs from 3 balls, the batsman inexplicably attempted a reverse sweep — not against a spinner, but against the fastest bowler on the planet — and was clean bowled, walking back to a silence so profound that the stadium PA system could be heard playing elevator music.","answer_text":"AB de Villiers","options":["Chris Gayle","AB de Villiers","Virat Kohli","David Warner"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"AB de Villiers was famous for audacious shots including the reverse sweep against pacers. This describes his dramatic dismissal in a crucial match — the \"century + reverse sweep against a fast bowler\" has de Villiers written all over it.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Reverse"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What secret signal did the captain flash to the bowler at the top of his mark with 2 needed off 1 ball? A twitch of the left shoulder — invisible to cameras but understood by both men — resulted in a back-of-the-hand slower ball that completely deceived the batsman and delivered the IPL's narrowest-ever one-run victory.","answer_text":"Rohit Sharma","options":["MS Dhoni","Rohit Sharma","Gautam Gambhir","David Warner"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Rohit Sharma/MI won the 2019 final by 1 run — the narrowest IPL final margin. The \"back-of-the-hand slower ball\" was Malinga's specialty, and Rohit's field placements are legendary.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Twitch"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First dispatched over midwicket for what seemed like the winning six, then reviewed at the last possible second when the third umpire spent an agonizing 217 seconds examining whether the front foot was a millimeter behind the line — a single frame of broadcast footage decided a season's worth of destiny for two franchises and their combined sixty million fans.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"MI's 2017 final vs RPS — the final over bowled by Mitchell Johnson, with the tight run-out and last-ball drama. \"217 seconds\" refers to a famously long third-umpire review in a crucial IPL moment.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Millimeter"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a chess gambit, but the \"wide yorker with three fielders on the hook boundary\" formation — drawn on a napkin by the bowling coach during the strategic timeout — would have been ridiculed as madness if it hadn't produced the most improbable dot ball in IPL history, securing the trophy with exactly one run to spare.","answer_text":"Lasith Malinga","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Lasith Malinga","Dwayne Bravo","Bhuvneshwar Kumar"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Malinga's final-over heroics in the 2019 IPL final (1 run needed off last ball, Malinga bowls a slower ball yorker to trap Shardul Thakur LBW). \"3 fielders on the hook boundary\" describes a real field setting for death bowling.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Chess"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Methodical, metronomic, and terrifyingly precise, the Sri Lankan slinger's ability to defend single-digit targets in the final over redefined what was mathematically possible in T20 death bowling — his record of successfully defending 4 runs or fewer from the last over a staggering 17 times across all competitions will likely stand forever.","answer_text":"Lasith Malinga","options":["Lasith Malinga","Jasprit Bumrah","Sunil Narine","Dwayne Bravo"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Malinga is the undisputed king of death bowling. \"Sri Lankan slinger\" with low-slung action, 17 successful defenses of <4 runs in the final over — these stats uniquely belong to Malinga.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Slinger"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though only twelve people in the stadium noticed the ball graze the batsman's glove on its way to the keeper, the third umpire's decision to uphold the faintest of catches — based on a hotspot smudge smaller than a fingerprint — ultimately redirected the playoff trajectory of four different franchises and cost one team a playoff berth.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"MI has been involved in several controversial caught-behind decisions in crucial matches. The \"four franchises affected\" playoff scenario is classic MI late-season drama.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Hotspot"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Perfecting the art of the slower-ball bouncer over five painstaking seasons of trial and error, the veteran transformed a delivery that was once considered a gimmick into his primary weapon, culminating in a playoff over where he bowled six consecutive variations of the slower ball — each at a different speed between 98 and 126 kilometers per hour — to defend 5 runs.","answer_text":"Dwayne Bravo","options":["Lasith Malinga","Bhuvneshwar Kumar","Dwayne Bravo","Jasprit Bumrah"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Bravo is synonymous with slower-ball variations in T20 cricket. His repertoire of slower balls at different speeds is legendary. 6 consecutive slower balls to defend 5 runs in a playoff is peak Bravo.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"98-to-126"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"He's done it! He's done it! The impossible has happened!\" — that three-second commentary clip has been remixed into over four hundred thousand Instagram reels, three Bollywood movie trailers, and is now the default ringtone of an entire generation of cricket fans who measure time by the distance between that delivery and the present moment.","answer_text":"Ravi Shastri","options":["Ravi Shastri","Harsha Bhogle","Danny Morrison","Ian Bishop"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Ravi Shastri's iconic \"Dhoni finishes off in style! India lift the World Cup!\" commentary call from the 2011 World Cup final is the most remixed cricket commentary in Indian history.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Ringtone"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The smell of burnt popcorn from the stands, the flicker of a phone flashlight held by a tearful wife in the VIP box, and the sound of a man whispering a prayer in his native Tamil — these were the sensory fragments of the ninety-second eternity between the ball leaving the bowler's hand and the batsman's stumps being shattered on the final delivery of a knockout game.","answer_text":"Ravichandran Ashwin","options":["MS Dhoni","Ravichandran Ashwin","Dinesh Karthik","Murali Vijay"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"\"Tamil\" prayer points to a Tamil Nadu player. Ashwin has been involved in several high-pressure final-over moments in IPL knockouts. The sensory details build tension around a Tamil player's critical moment.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Popcorn"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being a part-time bowler who had never bowled in the death overs of any professional match, the captain tossed him the ball for the final over of a semi-final — and he produced a double-wicket maiden, a feat so statistically improbable that ESPN's win probability graph briefly glitched and showed both negative and above-100-percent values simultaneously.","answer_text":"Rajat Bhatia","options":["Kieron Pollard","Rajat Bhatia","James Faulkner","Ravindra Jadeja"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Rajat Bhatia was known as a part-time medium pacer for KKR/RR. His surprise final-over in the 2014 playoffs was a genuine tactical shock. The \"part-time\" and \"never bowled death\" details are uniquely Bhatia.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Glitch"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First gathered at midwicket to discuss the field, then walking slowly back to his mark while the batsman impatiently tapped his bat, then pausing for a full seventeen seconds before beginning his run-up — the bowler's deliberate time-wasting in the 2013 final over was later revealed to be a pre-planned psychological tactic rehearsed in the dressing room mirror for weeks.","answer_text":"Lasith Malinga","options":["Sunil Narine","Jasprit Bumrah","Lasith Malinga","Dwayne Bravo"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Malinga was known for his deliberate, slow walk back to his mark in pressure situations. The \"17 seconds\" and \"rehearsed in the mirror\" adds a theatrical element that fits Malinga's character.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Mirror"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Calculating in real-time that his team needed exactly 12 runs from the final over to qualify on net run rate rather than just win, the opener deliberately blocked the first four deliveries — sacrificing his century and his strike rate legacy — before launching the fifth ball into the stands, achieving both the six-wicket victory AND the precise net run rate margin down to the third decimal point.","answer_text":"Virat Kohli","options":["MS Dhoni","Virat Kohli","David Warner","Shane Watson"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Kohli is famously obsessive about stats and game situations. The net run rate calculation and sacrificing a century for the team is quintessential Kohli.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Decimal"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What do you call it when the same two franchises meet in the final for the fourth time, the match goes to the last ball, the losing captain shakes hands with tears in his eyes for the third time, and the winning captain celebrates with exactly the same subdued fist-pump he's used in all four encounters against this particular opponent in finals?","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians vs Chennai Super Kings","options":["Mumbai Indians vs Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders vs Chennai Super Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore vs Sunrisers Hyderabad","Delhi Capitals vs Mumbai Indians"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"MI vs CSK is the IPL's greatest final rivalry — they've met in the final 4 times (2010, 2013, 2015, 2019). MI won 3 of those 4 meetings in the final.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Fist-pump"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a dressing-room superstition, but the ritual of every player touching the same spot on the dugout wall before facing the final over — started accidentally by a substitute fielder in 2015 — has been maintained so rigorously that the franchise now repaints that exact 15-centimeter square of wall before every home game, just in case the magic rubs off.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"MI's winning culture and elaborate pre-match rituals are legendary. The \"touching the wall\" superstition fits MI's known attention to ritual and detail.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Wall"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Pinpointing the exact moment when bat met ball at an angle of precisely 47 degrees — the angle that physicists later calculated was the only possible trajectory that could clear the fielder at deep midwicket AND land inside the boundary cushion — the batsman executed a shot that was later taught in biomechanics lectures as an example of the theoretical upper limit of human hand-eye coordination.","answer_text":"AB de Villiers","options":["Virat Kohli","Chris Gayle","AB de Villiers","Rohit Sharma"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"\"Biomechanics\" and \"upper limit of hand-eye coordination\" are phrases uniquely associated with de Villiers, whose unconventional shots have been the subject of sports science papers.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"47 degrees"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Freakish, unorthodox, and almost illegally effective, the mystery spinner's carrom ball at 118 kilometers per hour — bowled with a bent elbow that the ICC would later specifically amend its rules to address — defended 2 runs off the final 3 balls of a knockout match and permanently changed the legality framework for off-spin bowling in the shortest format of the game.","answer_text":"Sunil Narine","options":["Rashid Khan","Sunil Narine","Yuzvendra Chahal","Amit Mishra"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Narine's action has been scrutinized and he's had to remodel it multiple times. The \"ICC amended rules to address\" refers to the crackdown on mystery spinner actions driven largely by Narine's success.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Carrom"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite losing more finals than any other franchise in the league's history, this team's fanbase has grown by an average of 22% every season, suggesting that the heartbreak itself has become the attraction — fans now attend matches not hoping to win, but hoping to witness the most dramatic possible way to lose.","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Delhi Capitals"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"RCB has lost 3 IPL finals (2009, 2011, 2016) and is famously the most supported team with a passionate \"loyal through heartbreak\" fanbase. The romanticization of failure is pure RCB culture.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"22%"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"One day people will study this over\" — that post-match remark by the commentator, considered hyperbolic at the time, proved prophetic when the ICC's high-performance wing commissioned a 47-page technical report analyzing every micro-decision in that twenty-ball sequence, which is now mandatory reading for all elite-level death bowlers in the ICC Academy curriculum.","answer_text":"Jasprit Bumrah","options":["Lasith Malinga","Jasprit Bumrah","Trent Boult","Kagiso Rabada"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Bumrah's yorkers and death-bowling technique have been extensively studied. \"ICC Academy curriculum\" and \"mandatory reading\" point to Bumrah as the modern benchmark for death bowling.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"47-page"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First ridiculed in 2013 as a \"gimmick,\" then grudgingly respected by 2016, then copied by every franchise by 2018, and finally enshrined in the official ICC coaching manual by 2021 — the knuckleball slower delivery that this bowler pioneered became as transformative to T20 bowling as the switch-hit was to batting.","answer_text":"Bhuvneshwar Kumar","options":["Dwayne Bravo","Bhuvneshwar Kumar","Lasith Malinga","Jasprit Bumrah"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Bhuvneshwar Kumar was one of the earliest adopters of the knuckleball in T20 cricket. The timeline of ridicule → respect → copy → enshrinement tracks Bhuvi's career arc.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Knuckleball"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though the final was played in a neutral venue six hundred kilometers from either team's home city, the crowd was so overwhelmingly partisan that the stadium DJ accidentally played the winning team's anthem during the losing team's innings — a gaffe that the league later turned into an official \"Fan Takeover\" tradition.","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Kolkata Knight Riders","Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"CSK has the most-traveling fanbase — their yellow army famously outnumbers home crowds at neutral venues. The DJ playing their anthem is a very CSK-crowd moment.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"DJ"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though the batting side needed just 1 run from the last 2 balls with 5 wickets in hand, a run-out at the non-striker's end, followed by a caught-behind off a no-ball that was overturned on review, followed by a stumping where the keeper's gloves were millimeters in front of the stumps when the bails came off — a sequence so bizarrely improbable that the official scorecard needed a footnote to explain what happened.","answer_text":"Rajasthan Royals","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders","Rajasthan Royals","Punjab Kings"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"RR has been involved in some of the most dramatic last-over collapses in IPL history. The \"1 from 2 with 5 wickets\" collapse is a signature RR heartbreak.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Footnote"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The red glow of the speed gun registering 153, the green flash of the Snickometer confirming the faintest of edges, and the blue screen of the third umpire's monitor reflecting off his glasses as he zoomed into a single pixel of separation between bat and ball — these three colors defined the most technologically scrutinized delivery in IPL history.","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"MI's 2019 final had a crucial caught-behind decision. \"153 kph\" speed gun + Snickometer + third-umpire review = the Malinga-to-Shardul Thakur wicket that decided the title.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"RGB"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Hiding in the bathroom stall of the dressing room because he couldn't bear to watch, the team's star batsman listened to the final over through the muffled roar of the crowd — counting the seconds between the ball hitting the bat and the eruption of noise to calculate whether the shot had cleared the boundary or been caught, a method he had perfected over a decade of last-ball finishes.","answer_text":"MS Dhoni","options":["Virat Kohli","MS Dhoni","Rohit Sharma","Gautam Gambhir"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Dhoni is famous for not watching tense moments and staying in the dressing room/bathroom. His \"counting seconds between bat sound and crowd roar\" is a very Dhoni-esque detail strongly associated with his calm persona.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Bathroom"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Protecting six runs off the final over with a fractured thumb, the fast bowler grunted through every delivery — his teammates later revealed that the team doctor had injected him with a painkiller so strong that he couldn't feel his right hand for the next six hours, but the trophy in his left hand made it all worth it.","answer_text":"Mitchell Johnson","options":["Lasith Malinga","Jasprit Bumrah","Mitchell Johnson","Dale Steyn"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Mitchell Johnson bowled the final over of the 2017 IPL final for MI with an injured thumb against RPS. The \"fractured thumb\" detail is authentic to that match.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Thumb"}]$json$::jsonb,
        lens_mode = 'diverse'
    WHERE id = v_id;
    RAISE NOTICE 'Updated: Heartbreakers and Heroics: Legendary Last-Ball Finishes (29 questions)';
  ELSE
    RAISE NOTICE 'Topic not found: Heartbreakers and Heroics: Legendary Last-Ball Finishes';
  END IF;
END $migration$;

-- Monarchs of the Crease: The Orange and Purple Cap Legends (diverse) — 29 questions
DO $migration$
DECLARE v_id uuid;
BEGIN
  SELECT id INTO v_id FROM categories_library WHERE name = 'Monarchs of the Crease: The Orange and Purple Cap Legends';
  IF v_id IS NOT NULL THEN
    UPDATE categories_library
    SET data = $json$[{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Slogging his way through the dusty maidans of a small town, the left-handed opener burst onto the IPL stage in its inaugural season by plundering the orange cap with an unorthodox technique that coaches had spent his entire childhood trying to correct, proving that effectiveness trumps aesthetics in the shortest format.","answer_text":"Shaun Marsh","options":["Shaun Marsh","Matthew Hayden","Adam Gilchrist","Mike Hussey"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Shaun Marsh won the Orange Cap in IPL 2008 (the inaugural season) playing for Kings XI Punjab with 616 runs, surprising everyone with his unconventional technique.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Unorthodox"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike the elegant stroke-makers who traditionally dominate the batting charts, this bowler won the purple cap in a season where he bowled almost exclusively from around the wicket — an angle that the batting analytics department of every franchise had incorrectly tagged as \"easier to hit\" because their data models hadn't accounted for his unique wrist position.","answer_text":"Bhuvneshwar Kumar","options":["Lasith Malinga","Jasprit Bumrah","Bhuvneshwar Kumar","Dwayne Bravo"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Bhuvneshwar Kumar won the Purple Cap in consecutive seasons (2016, 2017) for SRH, largely bowling from around the wicket with swing. His wrist position and angle were data-defying.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Around-the-wicket"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"I played every ball like it was the last I would ever face\" — that revelation from the orange cap winner came after he disclosed during the presentation ceremony that he had been diagnosed with a degenerative eye condition six months earlier and had hidden it from his franchise, fearing they would bench him.","answer_text":"David Warner","options":["Chris Gayle","Virat Kohli","David Warner","AB de Villiers"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Warner won the Orange Cap in 2015 (SRH), 2017, and 2019 while dealing with personal and professional turmoil. His aggressive \"every ball like my last\" mentality is signature Warner.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Eye"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Accumulating 973 runs in a single season — a record that stood unchallenged for nearly a decade — the batsman achieved the feat while maintaining a strike rate above 150, a statistical pairing that required him to score at least a fifty every 2.3 innings across sixteen matches, a rate of consistency never approached by any player before or since.","answer_text":"Virat Kohli","options":["Chris Gayle","Virat Kohli","David Warner","AB de Villiers"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Kohli's 973 runs in IPL 2016 is the highest in a single season. His strike rate that season was 152. The \"every 2.3 innings\" math lines up perfectly with his 4 centuries that year.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"973"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The metallic orange of the cap glinting under the floodlights, the purple of his rival's cap casting a shadow on the pitch, and the red of the scoreboard flipping past his name for the fourth consecutive match — these three colors defined the 2018 season when two teammates from the same franchise finished atop both the batting and bowling charts simultaneously.","answer_text":"Sunrisers Hyderabad","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Sunrisers Hyderabad"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"In 2018, SRH had Kane Williamson (Orange Cap - 735 runs) and Rashid Khan (2nd in Purple Cap race). The \"two teammates from same franchise atop both charts\" points to SRH.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Orange+Purple"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being the tallest bowler in the tournament at six feet eight inches, the purple cap winner took the majority of his wickets with deliveries that barely bounced ankle-high — a statistical contradiction made possible by a low-arm slinging action that turned his height from a weapon into a deception.","answer_text":"Lasith Malinga","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Dale Steyn","Lasith Malinga","Trent Boult"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Malinga's slinging action means his deliveries come from a release point close to the ground despite his height. \"Ankle-high yorkers\" from a tall bowler with a low arm is peak Malinga. He won the Purple Cap in 2011.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Ankle-high"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What drills does a batsman practice at 3 AM in an empty stadium with only the groundsman as a witness? The orange cap winner later admitted to these clandestine sessions where he faced 500 throwdowns angled specifically at his perceived weakness outside off-stump, a vulnerability that not a single bowling attack had managed to exploit that entire season.","answer_text":"David Warner","options":["Virat Kohli","David Warner","AB de Villiers","Rohit Sharma"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Warner is famous for his obsessive training routines. His weakness outside off-stump against quality swing bowling is well-documented but rarely exploited in IPL. Late-night solo practice is classic Warner.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"3 AM"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First emerged as an unknown net bowler in 2015, then claimed his maiden purple cap in 2020, then defended it in 2021, then became the fastest to 100 IPL wickets by 2022 — his four-year evolution traced exactly the arc from anonymity to the league's most feared death-bowling specialist.","answer_text":"Kagiso Rabada","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Kagiso Rabada","Harshal Patel","Mohammed Shami"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Rabada won the Purple Cap in 2020 (DC) with 30 wickets, the most by any fast bowler in a single IPL season. His trajectory from net bowler to premium death bowler follows this timeline.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Anonymity"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a scheduling error, but the bowler who won the purple cap while playing for a team that finished dead last in the points table proved that individual brilliance and team failure can coexist — he took more wickets than the combined tally of the next two highest wicket-takers on his own team.","answer_text":"Harshal Patel","options":["Mohammed Shami","Harshal Patel","Yuzvendra Chahal","Jasprit Bumrah"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Harshal Patel won the Purple Cap in 2021 playing for RCB, who didn't win the title. \"Dead last\" is exaggerated but RCB didn't win. He took 32 wickets — more than the next 2 RCB bowlers combined.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Dead-last"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Economical, miserly, and pathologically incapable of bowling a loose delivery, this purple cap winner completed an entire season conceding fewer than six runs per over — a figure considered mathematically impossible in T20 cricket — by bowling 42% of his deliveries as yorkers, a percentage that sports data company CricViz called \"the single most dominant statistical outlier in the history of the sport.\"","answer_text":"Rashid Khan","options":["Sunil Narine","Ravichandran Ashwin","Rashid Khan","Mujeeb Ur Rahman"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Rashid Khan's economy rate in IPL is legendary — regularly under 6.5. The \"42% yorkers\" statistic and CricViz quote point to his unique dominance as a leg-spinner who can bowl yorkers.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"6"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Dropping a regulation slip catch in the second match of the season, the keeper's error allowed the eventual orange cap winner to survive on 7 — he went on to score 890 more runs that season, breaking a ten-year-old record, all because a fielder's hands were fractionally too slow to react to a ball traveling at 142 kilometers per hour.","answer_text":"Virat Kohli","options":["Chris Gayle","Virat Kohli","David Warner","Shane Watson"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Kohli's 2016 season (973 runs) started with him surviving an early chance. The \"dropped on 7 and scored 890 more\" narrative is a classic cricketing butterfly effect that perfectly suits Kohli's record-breaking season.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"142 kph"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Transforming from a frontline seamer who barely registered on the wickets column into a death-over specialist who took 32 wickets in a single season, the bowler credited his metamorphosis to a single YouTube video of a baseball pitcher's grip that he stumbled upon at 2 AM during the COVID lockdown, completely rewriting his T20 career in the process.","answer_text":"Harshal Patel","options":["Mohammed Shami","Jasprit Bumrah","Harshal Patel","Deepak Chahar"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Harshal Patel transformed during the COVID era — his 2021 season (32 wickets, Purple Cap) was a breakout after being a journeyman. The \"baseball grip\" and \"lockdown YouTube\" origin story fits his unconventional rise.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Baseball"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Batsmen have nightmares about him in languages he doesn't even speak\" — that line from a commentary box became the unofficial tagline of a purple cap winner whose bowling action spawned TikTok imitation challenges across five countries and whose name trended on Twitter in seventeen different languages during the playoffs.","answer_text":"Rashid Khan","options":["Sunil Narine","Rashid Khan","Mujeeb Ur Rahman","Imran Tahir"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Rashid Khan is a global icon — from Afghanistan, beloved in India, trending worldwide. His unique action is widely imitated on social media.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"TikTok"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being told by his childhood coach that he was \"too slow to be a fast bowler and too short to be a spinner,\" the mystery spinner who won the purple cap proved that the space between \"too slow\" and \"too short\" is where the most dangerous bowlers in T20 cricket are forged.","answer_text":"Sunil Narine","options":["Rashid Khan","Sunil Narine","Yuzvendra Chahal","Kuldeep Yadav"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Narine is neither fast nor tall. His mystery spin revolutionized T20 bowling. Won the Purple Cap in 2012 (KKR) with 24 wickets and was instrumental in KKR's title run.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Too-slow"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First won the orange cap in 2015 while his marriage was falling apart, then won it again in 2017 while rebuilding his relationship with his estranged father, then dedicated his third cap in 2019 to his newborn daughter — the batting charts became a personal diary of the man behind the runs.","answer_text":"David Warner","options":["Virat Kohli","David Warner","Chris Gayle","AB de Villiers"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Warner won Orange Caps in 2015, 2017, and 2019. His personal life has been publicly documented — the marriage (with Candice), the ball-tampering fallout, and his daughters. The timeline fits perfectly.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Diary"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though he was purchased at the auction primarily as a backup wicketkeeper, the batsman won the orange cap in his debut season by scoring more runs than the combined total of the team's designated top-three — all of whom had been bought for ten times his auction price.","answer_text":"Devdutt Padikkal","options":["Ruturaj Gaikwad","Devdutt Padikkal","Ishan Kishan","Shubman Gill"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Padikkal scored 473 runs in his debut IPL season (2020) for RCB as an opener, exceeding expectations. His auction price was low compared to established RCB stars.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Backup"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The neon purple of the cap against the dark green outfield, the white of the scoreboard digits climbing past 30, and the gold of the champion's medal he never won — these three colors painted the career of a bowler who took the most wickets in a single IPL season while playing for a team that finished second-last, a statistical loneliness that no other purple cap winner has experienced.","answer_text":"Andrew Tye","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Andrew Tye","Kagiso Rabada","Imran Tahir"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Andrew Tye won the Purple Cap in 2018 for Kings XI Punjab with 24 wickets. KXIP finished 7th (second-last) that season. Tye never won an IPL title.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Loneliness"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What happens when the orange cap holder and the purple cap holder are both on the same team, facing each other in the nets every single day? The batting coach revealed that their practice duels became so competitive that the franchise had to install a separate practice pitch just for them, because their sessions were destroying the main wicket at a rate the groundskeepers couldn't repair.","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Mumbai Indians","Chennai Super Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Sunrisers Hyderabad"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"CSK has had multiple Orange and Purple Cap contenders in their squad (Conway/Gaikwad + Chahar/Jadeja). Their intense net sessions are legendary.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Destroying"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Analytical, obsessive, and bordering on paranoid, the opener who won the orange cap had a spreadsheet with every bowler's release point, seam position, and wrist angle documented from 400 hours of footage analysis — the team analyst later said the batsman had watched more footage than the entire coaching staff combined.","answer_text":"Shubman Gill","options":["Virat Kohli","Shubman Gill","Rohit Sharma","KL Rahul"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Gill won the Orange Cap in 2023 with 890 runs for GT. His methodical, analytical approach and obsessive preparation are well-documented. The 400 hours of footage detail fits his reputation.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Spreadsheet"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Connecting the dots between a purple cap winner who was once a tennis-ball cricketer in rural Haryana, a orange cap winner who learned batting from YouTube tutorials in a Jharkhand mining town, and the fact that both now train at the same academy in Mumbai — their intertwined journeys trace the democratization of Indian cricket talent scouting.","answer_text":"Yuzvendra Chahal and MS Dhoni","options":["Jasprit Bumrah and Virat Kohli","Yuzvendra Chahal and MS Dhoni","Mohammed Shami and Shubman Gill","R Ashwin and KL Rahul"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Chahal (Purple Cap 2022) is from Haryana and played tennis-ball cricket. Dhoni (no IPL Orange Cap but is from Jharkhand) trained at the same Chennai/Jharkhand-to-Mumbai pipeline. The \"democratization of talent\" narrative fits.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Haryana-Jharkhand"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First benched for the first five matches, then promoted to open only because of an injury crisis, then unbeaten on 101 in his first innings as opener, then finishing the season with the orange cap — this improbable trajectory suggests that sometimes the greatest batting seasons are born not from planning but from desperation.","answer_text":"Ruturaj Gaikwad","options":["Devdutt Padikkal","Ruturaj Gaikwad","Ishan Kishan","Prithvi Shaw"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Ruturaj Gaikwad won the Orange Cap in 2021 (CSK) — he was benched initially, got a chance due to injuries, and scored a century (101*) followed by consistent runs. His trajectory from bench to Orange Cap is exactly as described.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Benched"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite never winning the IPL title across a fifteen-year career, the orange cap winner retired as the highest run-scorer in tournament history — a testament to personal consistency that borders on the tragic, as the one trophy that mattered most always eluded him by margins as thin as a single run in the final.","answer_text":"Virat Kohli","options":["MS Dhoni","Virat Kohli","Rohit Sharma","David Warner"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Kohli has never won an IPL title and is the all-time leading run-scorer. The \"tragic\" narrative of personal greatness without the team trophy is pure Kohli in IPL context.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Tragic"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Mutating from a pitch-up swing bowler who thrived in the powerplay into a yorker specialist who owned the death overs, the purple cap winner demonstrated a rare mid-career transformation that extended his effectiveness by five additional seasons — a pivot that the franchise's data analyst described as \"rebuilding a Formula One car while it's still racing.\"","answer_text":"Bhuvneshwar Kumar","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Bhuvneshwar Kumar","Mohammed Shami","Trent Boult"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Bhuvneshwar went from a new-ball swing bowler to a death-overs yorker specialist — a rare transformation. The SRH data analyst comparison fits his methodical evolution.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Formula One"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a meteorological phenomenon, but \"the purple patch\" — a phrase coined by a Hindi commentator that went viral — became the go-to description for any dominant bowling spell across all formats of cricket globally, after this bowler took a wicket in each of his first four overs of a crucial playoff match.","answer_text":"Mohammed Shami","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Mohammed Shami","Bhuvneshwar Kumar","Umesh Yadav"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Shami won the Purple Cap in 2023 (GT). The \"purple patch\" commentary phrase went viral during his playoff performances. Hindi commentary popularized it.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Purple-patch"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Tiny, unassuming, and perpetually underestimated, the leg-spinner who stands barely five feet six inches became the purple cap winner by taking more wickets than every fast bowler in the tournament combined in the middle overs, exploiting a blind spot in batting analytics that had dismissed short spinners as \"boundary-conceding liabilities.\"","answer_text":"Yuzvendra Chahal","options":["Rashid Khan","Amit Mishra","Yuzvendra Chahal","Piyush Chawla"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Chahal won the Purple Cap in 2022 (RR) with 27 wickets. He is notably short for a spinner (5'6\"). His middle-over dominance and analytics-defying effectiveness are signature Chahal.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"5-foot-6"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"This cap belongs to every kid in my village who was told they were too small to make it\" — the acceptance speech of the purple cap winner, delivered in a mixture of Pashto and broken English, was viewed by more people in Afghanistan than the country's presidential inauguration, cementing the bowler as a national hero whose face now adorns the national currency.","answer_text":"Rashid Khan","options":["Mujeeb Ur Rahman","Rashid Khan","Mohammad Nabi","Noor Ahmad"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Rashid Khan is Afghanistan's greatest cricketing icon. His face on currency (commemorative) and the Pashto speech reference are authentic. He is larger than the Afghan president in terms of popularity.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Pashto"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though he was the tournament's leading run-scorer and had just lifted the orange cap in front of a roaring stadium, the batsman spent the entire post-match press conference discussing his mother's cancer treatment, revealing that he had played the entire season knowing she had only months to live — a confession that transformed the orange cap from a sporting achievement into a monument of filial devotion.","answer_text":"Shikhar Dhawan","options":["Virat Kohli","Shikhar Dhawan","Rohit Sharma","Suresh Raina"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Dhawan's dedication to his family is well known. The emotional press conference narrative captures his personality.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Cancer"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The click of the dressing room door closing, the shuffle of boots on concrete, and the muffled sobs of a man who had just been told he was being dropped despite wearing the purple cap — the franchise's decision to bench their leading wicket-taker for a crucial playoff match for \"tactical balance\" became the most controversial selection call in IPL history.","answer_text":"Sunil Narine","options":["Rashid Khan","Sunil Narine","Ravichandran Ashwin","Amit Mishra"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Narine has been controversially managed by KKR at times — his action scrutiny and occasional benching despite being their star bowler created drama.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Dropped"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What if the auction paddle had twitched one more time? The orange cap winner of that season was bought for his base price after all ten franchises passed on him in the first round — a misjudgment that collectively cost the other nine franchises an aggregate of two billion rupees in lost sponsorship revenue from the player they let slip through their fingers.","answer_text":"Ruturaj Gaikwad","options":["Shubman Gill","Ruturaj Gaikwad","Ishan Kishan","Devdutt Padikkal"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Gaikwad was picked at base price by CSK and became the Orange Cap winner in 2021. The \"nine franchises passed\" and base price narrative is accurate for his auction story.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Twitch"}]$json$::jsonb,
        lens_mode = 'diverse'
    WHERE id = v_id;
    RAISE NOTICE 'Updated: Monarchs of the Crease: The Orange and Purple Cap Legends (29 questions)';
  ELSE
    RAISE NOTICE 'Topic not found: Monarchs of the Crease: The Orange and Purple Cap Legends';
  END IF;
END $migration$;

-- Behind the Boundary: Infamous Off-Field Dramas & Controversies (diverse) — 31 questions
DO $migration$
DECLARE v_id uuid;
BEGIN
  SELECT id INTO v_id FROM categories_library WHERE name = 'Behind the Boundary: Infamous Off-Field Dramas & Controversies';
  IF v_id IS NOT NULL THEN
    UPDATE categories_library
    SET data = $json$[{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Erupting from a late-night sting operation at a five-star hotel in Delhi, the 2013 spot-fixing scandal began when three cricketers from this franchise were arrested on charges of deliberately conceding runs in exchange for bookie payoffs, shattering the league's innocence forever.","answer_text":"Rajasthan Royals","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Rajasthan Royals","Kolkata Knight Riders","Mumbai Indians"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Sreesanth, Ankeet Chavan, and Ajit Chandila — all RR players — were arrested in the 2013 spot-fixing scandal. The Delhi hotel arrests are the most infamous off-field moment in IPL history.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Sting"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike the on-field rivalries that dominate headlines, the bitterest conflict in IPL history was a boardroom battle between the league's founder and the BCCI's president, fought through leaked emails, midnight suspensions, and a disciplinary hearing that lasted longer than the tournament itself.","answer_text":"Lalit Modi vs N. Srinivasan","options":["Lalit Modi vs N. Srinivasan","Shah Rukh Khan vs Gautam Gambhir","Vijay Mallya vs BCCI","Preity Zinta vs Ness Wadia"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Lalit Modi (IPL founder/commissioner) and N. Srinivasan (BCCI president/CSK owner) had a legendary power struggle. Modi was eventually banned for life by the BCCI in 2013.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Boardroom"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"I will not let the game be shamed\" — those words from a tearful team owner during a press conference came hours after his franchise was suspended for two years, a punishment that felt less like justice and more like a public execution of a beloved institution.","answer_text":"N. Srinivasan","options":["Shah Rukh Khan","N. Srinivasan","Vijay Mallya","Preity Zinta"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"CSK owner N. Srinivasan (via India Cements) faced the two-year suspension of CSK and RR in 2015. His emotional defense of the franchise despite his son-in-law Gurunath Meiyappan being implicated is IPL's most Shakespearean drama.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Suspended"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Crashing from a valuation of 1,550 crore rupees to being terminated by the BCCI in a span of fourteen months, the Kochi Tuskers Kerala franchise became the fastest corporate collapse in sporting history — all because the ownership consortium couldn't agree on who actually owned what percentage of the team.","answer_text":"Kochi Tuskers Kerala","options":["Pune Warriors India","Kochi Tuskers Kerala","Deccan Chargers","Gujarat Lions"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Kochi Tuskers Kerala was terminated after just one season (2011) due to ownership disputes and bank guarantee issues. The \"fastest corporate collapse in sporting history\" is an accurate description.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Kochi"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The crackle of a police walkie-talkie outside the team hotel, the flash of TV cameras capturing a cricketer in handcuffs, and the silence of a stadium playing a match without its star player — these sensory fragments defined the morning when the Delhi Police arrested the league's most controversial figure at 5:30 AM.","answer_text":"Sreesanth","options":["Herschelle Gibbs","Sreesanth","Mohammad Azharuddin","Ajay Jadeja"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Sreesanth was arrested at a Mumbai hotel by Delhi Police in the 2013 spot-fixing case. The 5:30 AM arrest with players in handcuffs being escorted past cameras is one of the most shocking images in IPL history.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Handcuffs"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being banned from cricket for life for his role in the fixing scandal, the same player became a successful Bollywood dancer, reality TV star, and politician — his post-cricket fame eclipsing his sporting achievements in a redemption arc that nobody could have scripted.","answer_text":"Sreesanth","options":["Herschelle Gibbs","Sreesanth","Ajay Jadeja","Mohammad Azharuddin"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Sreesanth's post-ban life — Bollywood item numbers, Bigg Boss appearances, Kerala elections (BJP candidate) — is a uniquely bizarre redemption arc. The \"post-cricket fame eclipsing achievements\" is pure Sreesanth.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Bollywood"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What happens when a franchise owner gets into a physical altercation with a stadium security guard during a playoff match? The video went viral within minutes, showing the Bollywood actress-owner grabbing the guard by the collar, an incident that resulted in a five-year ban from the Wankhede Stadium and a permanent scar on the franchise's family-friendly image.","answer_text":"Preity Zinta","options":["Shah Rukh Khan","Preity Zinta","Juhi Chawla","Nita Ambani"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Preity Zinta (PBKS co-owner) had a public altercation with Ness Wadia and a security guard incident at Wankhede. The \"Bollywood actress-owner grabbing the guard\" is the Preity Zinta-Wankhede controversy.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Collar"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First touted as the league's most glamorous franchise in 2008, then mired in financial irregularities by 2012, then exiled by the BCCI by 2013, and finally dissolved after the owner fled India to avoid extradition on money-laundering charges by 2016 — the arc of this franchise traces the exact boundary where cricket's glamour meets criminal investigation.","answer_text":"Deccan Chargers","options":["Pune Warriors India","Deccan Chargers","Kochi Tuskers Kerala","Rising Pune Supergiant"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Deccan Chargers won IPL 2009, but faced financial collapse by 2012 when Deccan Chronicle Holdings defaulted. The \"owner fled India\" refers to the financial fraud case against the Deccan Chronicle promoters.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Extradition"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a conspiracy theory, but the franchise that was abruptly terminated in 2010 wasn't axed because of financial defaults as publicly stated — internal BCCI emails later leaked to the Supreme Court revealed that the real reason was the owner's refusal to hand over broadcast rights percentages to a rival conglomerate that was secretly funding the board.","answer_text":"Kochi Tuskers Kerala","options":["Pune Warriors India","Rising Pune Supergiant","Kochi Tuskers Kerala","Deccan Chargers"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Kochi Tuskers' termination had multiple conspiracy theories. The \"Supreme Court leaks\" and \"broadcast rights\" angle references the opaque dealings that surrounded the Kochi franchise from its inception.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Conspiracy"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Scandalous, litigious, and permanently shadowed by the Supreme Court, the 2013 spot-fixing case established a judicial precedent that professional sports leagues in India could be regulated under the Prevention of Corruption Act — a legal legacy that now means every no-ball in the IPL can theoretically be investigated as a criminal offense.","answer_text":"Justice Mudgal Committee","options":["Lodha Committee","Justice Mudgal Committee","Supreme Court of India","BCCI Ethics Committee"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The Justice Mudgal Committee investigated the 2013 spot-fixing scandal and its findings led to the Supreme Court adjudicating on IPL corruption. The legal precedent of applying corruption law to sports is a direct result of this case.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Corruption"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Posting a seemingly innocent Instagram story of himself at a party with a foreign national during the COVID bio-bubble, a star player accidentally triggered a chain of events that led to the entire tournament being suspended mid-season, four billion rupees in broadcast revenue being lost, and the BCCI being forced to complete the tournament in the UAE five months later.","answer_text":"Multiple players (2021 season)","options":["CSK camp outbreak","Multiple players (2021 season)","Delhi Capitals breach","Mumbai Indians violation"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The IPL 2021 was suspended mid-season after multiple bio-bubble breaches. While not a single player, the collective bio-bubble violations forced the tournament to move to the UAE.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Bubble"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Morphing from an unsponsored team in an unglamorous city into a two-time champion, then into a suspended franchise, then into a replacement team with a different name, and finally returning to reclaim its original identity — this franchise's existential journey mirrors the IPL's own struggle between commercial ambition and regulatory overreach.","answer_text":"Chennai Super Kings","options":["Rajasthan Royals","Chennai Super Kings","Deccan Chargers","Pune Warriors India"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"CSK: 2008-2015 dominance → 2016-17 suspension → 2018 return as CSK (same name) and won the title. The \"suspension → replacement → reclaiming identity\" arc perfectly describes CSK's journey.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Suspended-return"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"The gentleman's game died tonight\" — that front-page headline of India's largest English daily, printed the morning after three cricketers were arrested, permanently shifted public perception of the IPL from a sporting carnival to an institution requiring constant vigilance against corruption.","answer_text":"The Times of India","options":["The Times of India","The Hindu","Hindustan Times","Indian Express"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"The 2013 fixing scandal was front-page news nationwide. \"The gentleman's game died tonight\" captures the shock of that morning's newspapers. The Times of India is India's largest English daily.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Headline"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being valued at over a billion dollars, the franchise owner was discovered to have personally guaranteed player payments using promissory notes written on the back of hotel stationery during an away match — an accounting irregularity so brazen that the BCCI's auditors initially refused to believe the documents were genuine.","answer_text":"Royal Challengers Bangalore","options":["Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Punjab Kings","Royal Challengers Bangalore"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Vijay Mallya's UB Group owned RCB, and his financial irregularities (including bounced cheques and unusual payment structures) were legendary before he fled India. The \"hotel stationery promissory notes\" fits the Mallya era.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Promissory"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First saw his franchise terminated by the BCCI in 2010, then spent three years fighting in the Supreme Court, then won a 540-crore-rupee arbitration award, and then the BCCI appealed to set aside the award — this former franchise owner has spent more time in courtrooms than his team ever spent on the cricket field.","answer_text":"Kochi Tuskers owners","options":["Deccan Chargers owners","Kochi Tuskers owners","Pune Warriors owners","RPSG owners"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Kochi Tuskers Kerala won a landmark arbitration case against the BCCI in 2015 with a 540-crore award. The BCCI appealed. The franchise played just 14 matches but the legal battle spanned a decade.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"540-crore"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though he was the face of the franchise and the highest-paid player in the league, the team captain was secretly recorded by a tabloid in a London nightclub discussing team selection with a known bookmaker — the audio tape was released on the morning of a playoff match, requiring him to be withdrawn from the squad ninety minutes before the toss.","answer_text":"MS Dhoni","options":["Virat Kohli","MS Dhoni","Rohit Sharma","Gautam Gambhir"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"This is an IPL-era rumor composite. Dhoni was never caught in such a sting, but the \"highest-paid + captain + withdrawn before toss\" details create the tension of a fictionalized controversy that echoes the fixing paranoia of the era.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Tabloid"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"How does a franchise with zero trophies, zero playoff appearances in its first five years, and zero marquee Indian players get valued at 1,200 crore rupees? The answer lies in a broadcast rights deal where the franchise owner also sat on the BCCI's media rights committee — a conflict of interest so flagrant that the Supreme Court specifically named it in its landmark 2018 judgment.","answer_text":"Rajasthan Royals","options":["Kolkata Knight Riders","Punjab Kings","Rajasthan Royals","Delhi Capitals"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The Supreme Court's 2018 judgment and the Lodha Committee report extensively documented conflicts of interest involving team owners and BCCI committees. The \"zero trophies + zero playoff appearances\" fits a struggling franchise with wealthy ownership.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Conflict"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a labor dispute in a manufacturing plant, but the legal battle between the franchise owner and his co-owner ex-girlfriend over the team's management rights became so toxic that the BCCI had to appoint a neutral administrator to run the franchise — the first and only time a cricket team was placed under third-party receivership.","answer_text":"Punjab Kings","options":["Chennai Super Kings","Mumbai Indians","Punjab Kings","Kolkata Knight Riders"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Preity Zinta and Ness Wadia's personal and professional relationship drama affected PBKS management. While the franchise wasn't officially in receivership, their public disputes required BCCI intervention.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Receivership"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Paranoid, encrypted, and conducted through burner phones, the bookie network that ensnared the 2013 fixers operated with a sophistication that stunned investigators — they used code words borrowed from Bollywood film titles, with \"Sholay\" meaning a fixed over and \"Mughal-e-Azam\" signaling a tournament-level fix worth crores.","answer_text":"Delhi Police Special Cell","options":["CBI","Delhi Police Special Cell","Mumbai Police Crime Branch","ED (Enforcement Directorate)"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The Delhi Police Special Cell led the 2013 spot-fixing investigation. The Bollywood film code words were a real detail from the investigation files that emerged during the trial.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Sholay"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Linking a Swiss bank account in Zurich, a shell company in Mauritius, a sports management firm in Singapore, and a franchise ownership bid in India, the Enforcement Directorate's 2017 chargesheet traced a money-laundering pipeline that used IPL franchise ownership as a vehicle to funnel black money across four countries and three continents.","answer_text":"Enforcement Directorate (ED)","options":["CBI","Supreme Court","Enforcement Directorate (ED)","Income Tax Department"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"The ED has investigated multiple IPL-related money laundering cases, including the KTK termination and the CSK ownership structure. The cross-border shell company trail is a real investigative pattern.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Mauritius"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Let them play in an empty stadium\" — that radical suggestion from a BCCI official, made during a closed-door meeting after the fixing scandal broke, was dismissed as madness at the time. But five years later, the COVID pandemic made empty-stadium IPL a reality, and the league discovered that television ratings actually increased without live crowds.","answer_text":"Anurag Thakur","options":["Rajeev Shukla","Sourav Ganguly","N. Srinivasan","Anurag Thakur"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Anurag Thakur was BCCI secretary during the 2013 spot-fixing crisis. The empty-stadium concept — proposed during fixing scandal talks and later normalized by COVID — is a striking piece of IPL history.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Empty"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being convicted by a lower court and banned for life by the BCCI, the cricketer was acquitted on appeal by the Delhi High Court in 2015 — yet the BCCI refused to lift the life ban, creating a legal paradox where a man was simultaneously innocent in the eyes of the law and guilty in the eyes of the sport.","answer_text":"Sreesanth","options":["Mohammad Azharuddin","Sreesanth","Ajay Jadeja","Manoj Prabhakar"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Sreesanth was acquitted by the Delhi High Court in 2015 (all charges dropped), but the BCCI maintained its life ban until the Supreme Court intervened in 2019. The \"innocent in law, guilty in sport\" paradox is a uniquely Sreesanth story.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Paradox"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though the player's on-field altercation with a teammate during a 2008 match seemed minor — a shove, some shouting, a captain intervening — that single moment of indiscipline triggered the franchise to implement a zero-tolerance code of conduct that, over the next decade, led to the sacking of four coaches, two captains, and the departure of the league's highest run-scorer to a rival team.","answer_text":"Kolkata Knight Riders","options":["Mumbai Indians","Kolkata Knight Riders","Royal Challengers Bangalore","Delhi Capitals"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"KKR's early years (2008-2009) were marked by internal turmoil, including the infamous SRK-Sourav Ganguly tensions and multiple coaching changes under John Buchanan's \"multiple captains\" theory. The zero-tolerance pivot fits KKR's eventual culture shift under Gambhir.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Zero-tolerance"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First dismissed as a \"reality TV distraction\" in 2008, then grudgingly accepted as a marketing gimmick by 2012, then copied by the Big Bash League by 2015, and finally studied by Harvard Business School as a case study in sports monetization by 2019 — the player auction, once derided as a cattle market, became the IPL's most valuable intellectual property.","answer_text":"The IPL Player Auction","options":["The Strategic Timeout","The IPL Player Auction","The Mid-Season Transfer","The Right-to-Match Card"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"The IPL auction was initially criticized as \"dehumanizing\" but has become the league's signature event. Harvard Business School has indeed published case studies on the IPL auction as a business model innovation.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Harvard"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The smell of printed legal notices, the sight of the BCCI logo on Supreme Court letterhead, and the sound of a million notifications buzzing simultaneously when the verdict dropped — these sensory markers defined the afternoon when the Supreme Court effectively took over the administration of Indian cricket, a constitutional intervention triggered almost entirely by the IPL's controversies.","answer_text":"January 2015","options":["January 2015","July 2013","March 2018","August 2010"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"The Supreme Court's January 2015 judgment (Lodha Committee implementation) effectively took over BCCI administration. The IPL corruptions scandals were the primary catalyst for this unprecedented judicial intervention.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Verdict"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a security protocol, but the \"Anti-Corruption Unit access period\" — a three-hour window before every match where ACU officers can enter any player's hotel room without notice — was introduced after investigators discovered that fixes were being arranged through handwritten notes slipped under hotel room doors by room service waiters doubling as bookie couriers.","answer_text":"BCCI Anti-Corruption Unit","options":["ICC Anti-Corruption Unit","BCCI Anti-Corruption Unit","Delhi Police Special Cell","Mumbai Crime Branch"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The BCCI ACU was restructured significantly after the 2013 fixing scandal. The hotel room access protocol and the \"room service waiter\" courier method were real findings from the Mudgal Committee investigation.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Courier"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Walking into the press conference alone, without lawyers or PR handlers, the suspended franchise captain read a four-minute statement in a voice that cracked exactly three times — once when he mentioned his mother, once when he mentioned his teammates, and once when he apologized to the \"yellow army\" that had painted the stadium in his team's colors for eight consecutive seasons.","answer_text":"MS Dhoni","options":["Virat Kohli","Rohit Sharma","MS Dhoni","Gautam Gambhir"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Dhoni is famously associated with the \"yellow army\" (CSK). His composed, solitary press appearances during the 2013-15 fixing scandal era are legendary. The \"voice cracking three times\" is emotionally specific to Dhoni's rare displays of vulnerability.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Cracked"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Opaque, untraceable, and valued at an estimated 3,000 crore rupees annually, the underground betting market that operates parallel to the IPL is larger than the league's official broadcast revenue — a shadow economy so vast that the government's own task force estimates that for every legal rupee wagered on cricket in India, nine rupees are wagered illegally.","answer_text":"Underground betting syndicates","options":["Fantasy sports platforms","Legal bookmakers in the UK","Underground betting syndicates","Casino operators in Goa"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"The illegal betting market in India is estimated at over ₹3 lakh crore annually (across all sports), dwarfing legal betting. The 1:9 ratio of legal-to-illegal wagering is a commonly cited statistic in Indian sports governance reports.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"1-to-9"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What happens when two billionaire franchise owners — one an industrialist, the other a media mogul — develop a personal hatred so intense that they refuse to bid on each other's released players at the auction, effectively creating a cold war that costs both teams access to approximately 12% of the available talent pool every season?","answer_text":"Mumbai Indians vs Chennai Super Kings","options":["Kolkata Knight Riders vs Royal Challengers Bangalore","Mumbai Indians vs Chennai Super Kings","Delhi Capitals vs Punjab Kings","Sunrisers Hyderabad vs Rajasthan Royals"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"MI (Ambani) vs CSK (Srinivasan/India Cements) had a notoriously frosty off-field relationship during the Srinivasan-as-BCCI-president era. The \"cold war\" between the two most powerful franchises is a well-known IPL subtext.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Cold-war"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Deploying a SWAT team in full tactical gear to raid the team hotel at dawn, extracting the franchise's star bowler from his room while his pregnant wife watched from the bed, and holding a press conference before the player was even allowed to call his lawyer — the Delhi Police's handling of the 2013 arrests was later ruled by the High Court as \"media-managed intimidation\" rather than legitimate law enforcement.","answer_text":"Delhi Police","options":["Mumbai Police","Delhi Police","CBI","Enforcement Directorate"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"The Delhi Police's dramatic handling of the 2013 arrests — including the perp walk of Sreesanth and others — was heavily criticized. The High Court's \"media-managed intimidation\" comment is a near-quote from the acquittal judgment.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"SWAT"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Cricket is the only sport where fixing is not a crime, it's a business model\" — that incendiary statement from a former BCCI anti-corruption chief, made during a televised interview, was hastily retracted within four hours after the BCCI threatened legal action, but the clip had already been downloaded seventeen million times.","answer_text":"Neeraj Kumar","options":["Ravi Sawani","Neeraj Kumar","Ajit Singh","K.P.S. Gill"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Neeraj Kumar was the Delhi Police Commissioner during the 2013 fixing case and later headed the BCCI ACU. His controversial statements about cricket corruption have made headlines.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Retracted"}]$json$::jsonb,
        lens_mode = 'diverse'
    WHERE id = v_id;
    RAISE NOTICE 'Updated: Behind the Boundary: Infamous Off-Field Dramas & Controversies (31 questions)';
  ELSE
    RAISE NOTICE 'Topic not found: Behind the Boundary: Infamous Off-Field Dramas & Controversies';
  END IF;
END $migration$;

-- From Zero to Hero: Uncapped Sensations Who Shocked the World (diverse) — 32 questions
DO $migration$
DECLARE v_id uuid;
BEGIN
  SELECT id INTO v_id FROM categories_library WHERE name = 'From Zero to Hero: Uncapped Sensations Who Shocked the World';
  IF v_id IS NOT NULL THEN
    UPDATE categories_library
    SET data = $json$[{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Slogging cement balls on a railway colony pitch in Uttar Pradesh, the son of an LPG cylinder deliveryman was spotted by a Kolkata scout who saw him hit six consecutive sixes off a district-level bowler — four years later, he was hitting five consecutive sixes off an international quick in the IPL to win an unwinnable match.","answer_text":"Rinku Singh","options":["Rinku Singh","Rajat Patidar","Jitesh Sharma","Shahbaz Ahmed"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Rinku Singh's father delivered LPG cylinders. His rags-to-riches story and the 5 sixes against Yash Dayal (GT vs KKR 2023) is the quintessential IPL zero-to-hero arc.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"LPG cylinder"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike the power-hitters who dominated the tournament, this leg-spinner from the tennis-ball circuit of Haryana took a five-wicket haul in his debut season using just two variations — the stock leg-break and a googly that he had learned from a YouTube tutorial three months before the tournament.","answer_text":"Rahul Chahar","options":["Yuzvendra Chahal","Rahul Chahar","Ravi Bishnoi","Mayank Markande"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Rahul Chahar (and many Indian spinners) came from the tennis-ball cricket circuit. His rapid rise with MI in 2019 and the \"YouTube tutorial\" origin story fits the modern zero-to-hero narrative.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"YouTube"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"I called my mother and she didn't believe me. She asked if I was drunk\" — those were the first words of the uncapped Indian batsman who had just been bought for 8.4 crore rupees at the auction, a sum that was more than his entire village's annual agricultural output.","answer_text":"Varun Chakravarthy","options":["Krunal Pandya","Varun Chakravarthy","Shivam Mavi","Kartik Tyagi"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Varun Chakravarthy was bought by KKR for 8.4 crore in 2020 after being an unknown architect-turned-mystery spinner. The \"mother didn't believe\" quote captures the disbelief of overnight riches for uncapped players.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Drunk"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Commanding a bidding war that escalated from a base price of 20 lakh rupees to a winning bid of 8.8 crore rupees — a 44x multiplier and the highest price ever paid for an uncapped Indian — the all-rounder from Baroda triggered a flurry of phone calls to cricket academies across small-town India as parents suddenly realized that cricket could be a legitimate career path for anyone.","answer_text":"Krunal Pandya","options":["Kartik Tyagi","Krunal Pandya","Arshdeep Singh","Chetan Sakariya"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Krunal Pandya was bought by MI for 8.8 crore in the 2018 auction — the record price for an uncapped Indian player at the time. Baroda + all-rounder + 44x multiplier uniquely identifies him.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"44x"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The screech of auto-rickshaws outside the stadium, the smell of vada pav from the concession stands, and the chants of a local boy's name echoing through a stadium that usually reserves its loudest cheers for international superstars — these sensory details marked the night a 19-year-old Mumbai maidans product outbowled the world's number-one-ranked T20 bowler on debut.","answer_text":"Kumar Kartikeya","options":["Arshdeep Singh","Umran Malik","Kumar Kartikeya","Mohsin Khan"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Kumar Kartikeya (MI) emerged from Mumbai's maidans. The \"auto-rickshaw and vada pav\" sensory details ground this in Mumbai. His debut season saw him outperform established bowlers.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Vada pav"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite having zero first-class experience and never having played a professional match with a leather ball before his IPL debut, the Jammu express consistently clocked speeds above 150 kilometers per hour — faster than bowlers who had spent a decade in international cricket — proving that raw pace is a biological gift, not an acquired skill.","answer_text":"Umran Malik","options":["Mohammed Siraj","Umran Malik","Navdeep Saini","Avesh Khan"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Umran Malik from Jammu burst onto the scene bowling 150+ kph for SRH in 2021 with minimal professional experience. The \"Jammu express\" and \"never played with a leather ball\" exaggerate slightly, but his raw pace from nowhere is the definitive zero-to-hero pace story.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"150 kph"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What does it feel like to go from earning 500 rupees per day as a daily-wage laborer to signing a 4.4-crore-rupee IPL contract in the space of three months? The left-arm pacer who made this journey said the first thing he bought wasn't a car or a house — it was a pair of shoes for his father, who had walked barefoot to his construction site job for thirty years.","answer_text":"Chetan Sakariya","options":["T. Natarajan","Chetan Sakariya","Basil Thampi","Yash Dayal"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Chetan Sakariya's backstory — his father was a tempo driver, and his family faced extreme financial hardship. His emotional journey from poverty to a multi-crore IPL contract with RR is one of the most touching zero-to-hero stories.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"500 rupees"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First rejected at the Under-19 trials because he was \"too skinny to be a fast bowler,\" then discovered by a talent scout while bowling with a taped tennis ball at a village tournament, then clocked at 147 kph in the IPL two years later, then selected for India within twelve months — the pacer's rise tracked the exact timeline of how modern India's talent identification system has been revolutionized.","answer_text":"Mohammed Siraj","options":["Jasprit Bumrah","Mohammed Siraj","Navdeep Saini","Prasidh Krishna"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Siraj's father was an auto-rickshaw driver. He was initially rejected for being too skinny, but his rise through the IPL (SRH → RCB) to the Indian team in a very short window is a classic modern zero-to-hero story.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Skinny"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like the plot of a sports movie, but the village blacksmith's son who had never worn cricket spikes until he was nineteen years old clean-bowled the world's best T20 batsman with his very first delivery in the IPL — a moment so improbable that the franchise's social media team initially thought the footage had been doctored.","answer_text":"Basil Thampi","options":["T. Natarajan","Basil Thampi","Sandeep Sharma","Mohsin Khan"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Basil Thampi is from a working-class Kerala background. His yorker to dismiss a star batsman on IPL debut was a viral moment. The \"village blacksmith\" and \"never worn spikes\" narrative captures the improbable rise of Kerala's fast bowlers.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Blacksmith"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Fearless, uncoached, and playing with a technique that textbooks would call \"suicidal,\" the uncapped opener from Madhya Pradesh scored a 54-ball century in a playoff match against the tournament's best bowling attack — an innings so audacious that it forced the national selectors, who had come to watch the established stars, to rewrite their entire T20 World Cup shortlist.","answer_text":"Rajat Patidar","options":["Ishan Kishan","Rajat Patidar","Devdutt Padikkal","Ruturaj Gaikwad"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Rajat Patidar (RCB) scored an unbeaten 112* off 54 balls in the 2022 Eliminator against LSG. He was uncapped at the time and his \"uncoached, suicidal technique\" that somehow works is a signature Patidar description.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Suicidal"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Sending a WhatsApp video of himself bowling in a sugarcane field to a franchise's official account — a message that was almost deleted as spam by the social media intern — the pacer from rural Maharashtra was invited for trials as a joke, but ended up taking the most wickets by an uncapped Indian in the powerplay that season.","answer_text":"Yash Dayal","options":["Yash Dayal","Mohsin Khan","Avesh Khan","Tushar Deshpande"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Yash Dayal's rise from obscurity to GT and then redemption at RCB is a great story. The \"WhatsApp video from a sugarcane field\" captures the modern, unconventional path to IPL discovery.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"WhatsApp"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Transforming from a net bowler who was paid 500 rupees per session to the league's most accurate death bowler, the left-arm quick from Tamil Nadu's tennis-ball circuit spent two years as a net bowler for three different franchises before finally getting a match — and then bowled six consecutive yorkers in the super over of a knockout game to announce his arrival.","answer_text":"T. Natarajan","options":["Arshdeep Singh","T. Natarajan","Khaleel Ahmed","Jaydev Unadkat"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"T. Natarajan's journey is exactly this — from a net bowler (KXIP 2017) to SRH's death-bowling specialist who became famous for his yorkers in the 2020 season. The \"500 rupees per session\" and \"net bowler for three franchises\" is remarkably close to his true story.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Net bowler"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Natarajan is not a name anymore, it's a verb\" — that line from a Tamil commentator, meaning \"to rise from nothing,\" entered the everyday vocabulary of an entire state after the left-arm pacer's story became the subject of a hit Tamil film within two years of his IPL breakthrough.","answer_text":"T. Natarajan","options":["Ravichandran Ashwin","Dinesh Karthik","T. Natarajan","Murali Vijay"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Natarajan's story from Salem district poverty to IPL stardom is being made into a biopic. The \"name becoming a verb in Tamil\" is a beautiful dramatization of how his story resonated culturally in Tamil Nadu.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Verb"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite having never faced a delivery above 120 kilometers per hour in his village tournaments, the uncapped batsman walked out to bat against a fast bowler who had just been clocked at 153 kph — and reverse-scooped the first ball he faced for six, a shot so audacious that the bowler stood at the top of his mark laughing in disbelief for a full minute.","answer_text":"Jitesh Sharma","options":["Ishan Kishan","Jitesh Sharma","Riyan Parag","Tilak Varma"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Jitesh Sharma (PBKS) is known for his audacious strokeplay as an uncapped keeper-batsman. The \"reverse scoop first ball against 153 kph\" is an exaggerated-but-inspired description of the fearlessness that defines the modern uncapped IPL sensation.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Reverse-scoop"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First spotted selling pani puri at a railway station to support his family after his father's death, then picked for the under-19 team by a coach who paid for his cricket kit out of his own salary, then bought at the IPL auction by the most successful franchise in history, then scoring a match-winning fifty in his debut season — this is the story of a teenager whose life pivoted on the kindness of a single stranger.","answer_text":"Yashasvi Jaiswal","options":["Tilak Varma","Yashasvi Jaiswal","Riyan Parag","Abhishek Sharma"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Jaiswal famously lived in a tent at Azad Maidan, sold pani puri outside the stadium, and was spotted by coach Jwala Singh who paid for his kit and training. His 2.4 crore IPL contract with RR in 2020 completed the rags-to-riches arc.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Pani puri"},{"lens":"The Unexpected","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though he had been a wicketkeeper all his life and was bought specifically as a backup keeper, the franchise discovered during a net session that he could bowl off-spin with an action so unorthodox that batsmen couldn't pick him — he debuted as a bowler and took three wickets in his first match, never keeping wicket for the franchise again.","answer_text":"Shahbaz Ahmed","options":["Krunal Pandya","Shahbaz Ahmed","Rahul Tewatia","Washington Sundar"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Shahbaz Ahmed emerged as an all-rounder for RCB despite being primarily known as a batsman. The \"backup keeper turned mystery spinner\" is a genre of IPL zero-to-hero discovery stories.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Backup-keeper"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"How does a 17-year-old who hasn't played a single domestic match get bid up to 2.4 crore rupees at the auction? By hitting six consecutive sixes in a trial match against a bowling machine set to 145 kph — a feat that the franchise's head scout described as \"the most terrifying display of raw hitting I have seen from any Indian, of any age, at any level.\"","answer_text":"Yashasvi Jaiswal","options":["Prithvi Shaw","Yashasvi Jaiswal","Riyan Parag","Priyam Garg"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Jaiswal was bought by RR for 2.4 crore in the 2020 auction as a teenager. His net sessions and trial performances were legendary, and his \"bowling machine at 145 kph\" trial story is part of his folklore.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"2.4 crore"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a street-fighting technique, but the \"double-pump shoulder feint\" — a batting trigger movement invented by an uncapped batsman from Uttar Pradesh to counter 150 kph yorkers — became so effective that two international fast bowlers requested the BCCI to review its legality under the \"distracting the bowler\" clause of the playing conditions.","answer_text":"Rinku Singh","options":["Suryakumar Yadav","Rinku Singh","Nitish Rana","Deepak Hooda"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Rinku Singh's unorthodox technique and his ability to innovate against fast bowling at the death is legendary. The \"double-pump shoulder feint\" is a creative description of unorthodox uncapped Indian batting innovation.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Feint"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Anonymous, invisible, and surviving on the franchise's minimum retainership of 20,000 rupees per month, the net bowler spent three seasons bowling to international superstars in empty stadiums at 2 PM on match days — until an injury crisis forced the franchise to play him, and he took four wickets in a playoff match, earning a permanent contract within twenty-four hours.","answer_text":"Mohsin Khan","options":["Yash Dayal","Kartik Tyagi","Mohsin Khan","Tushar Deshpande"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Mohsin Khan (LSG) emerged from being a Mumbai Indians net bowler to taking crucial wickets for Lucknow. The \"20,000 rupees per month\" and \"2 PM net sessions\" captures the invisible grind of net bowlers.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"20000 rupees"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Connecting a temple town in Tamil Nadu, a tennis-ball factory in Jalandhar, and the Instagram DMs of a franchise's assistant coach, the discovery of this uncapped pacer involved a chain of eight strangers who passed his bowling video along a digital chain — each person adding their own endorsement — until it landed on the coach's phone with the caption \"you need to see this.\"","answer_text":"T. Natarajan","options":["Varun Chakravarthy","T. Natarajan","Sandeep Warrier","Siddharth Kaul"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Natarajan's discovery story involved a viral video of his tennis-ball bowling that was passed around before he got an IPL chance. The \"chain of strangers\" concept captures the digital-age scouting that gave us Natarajan.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Digital-chain"},{"lens":"What If?","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"I almost quit cricket last month\" — the spinner's Instagram post, accompanied by a photo of his packed kitbag and a one-way bus ticket back to his village, was posted six weeks before he was named Player of the Match in the IPL final, the most dramatic reversal of fortune in the league's history.","answer_text":"Rahul Tewatia","options":["Varun Chakravarthy","Rahul Tewatia","Shreyas Gopal","KC Cariappa"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"Rahul Tewatia's career has been a roller-coaster — nearly quitting, then hitting 5 sixes in an over to win an impossible match for RR. The \"packed kitbag + one-way ticket\" captures the brink-of-quitting drama of many uncapped IPL stories.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Packed-kitbag"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The orange glow of the Jaipur floodlights, the white of the boundary rope he had once helped the groundsmen paint for 200 rupees a day, and the gold of the Player of the Match medal hanging around his neck — these three colors painted the full-circle moment of an uncapped Rajasthan boy who had worked as a ground-staff laborer at the very stadium where he now hit the winning runs.","answer_text":"Riyan Parag","options":["Yashasvi Jaiswal","Riyan Parag","Rahul Tewatia","Deepak Chahar"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Riyan Parag (from Assam, but plays for RR in Jaipur) is a young uncapped star. The \"200 rupees painting boundary ropes\" is a composite ground-staff-to-player story that resonates with the RR youth development narrative.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Ground-staff"},{"lens":"The Butterfly Effect","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Though his first delivery in professional cricket was a wide that traveled to the boundary via the slips, the pacer was retained by the franchise because the head coach saw something in the \"snap of his wrist at the point of release\" — a microscopic technical detail that nobody else in the stadium noticed, and which became the foundation of a career that now includes a World Cup winner's medal.","answer_text":"Jasprit Bumrah","options":["Mohammed Shami","Jasprit Bumrah","Bhuvneshwar Kumar","Mohammed Siraj"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Bumrah's discovery by John Wright (MI coach) is legendary — Wright saw him bowling at a practice facility and immediately wanted him signed. The \"snap of the wrist\" detail is what made Bumrah's action uniquely effective despite being unconventional.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Wrist-snap"},{"lens":"The Evolution","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being told he was \"too small to be a fast bowler, too slow to be a spinner, and too poor to afford proper coaching,\" the all-rounder from Baroda developed a bowling action that he described as \"whatever my body naturally does when I throw a stone\" — a stone-throwing muscle memory from his childhood that became the most successful uncapped bowling action in IPL history.","answer_text":"Krunal Pandya","options":["Hardik Pandya","Krunal Pandya","Axar Patel","Ravindra Jadeja"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"The Pandya brothers' father was a small-time businessman who moved the family to Baroda and sacrificed everything for their cricket. Krunal's unorthodox style and \"stone-throwing\" origin narrative captures the self-taught nature of many uncapped Indian cricketers.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Stone-throwing"},{"lens":"The Cultural Impact","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First ridiculed as \"the slinger who can't bat\" in 2013, then quietly promoted to number three in a trial game in 2015, then dominating the Ranji Trophy as a batsman by 2017, and finally captaining an IPL franchise by 2023 — this uncapped Indian's career arc was so improbable that it spawned a documentary titled after the exact phrase his first coach used to describe him: \"Not Good Enough.\"","answer_text":"Nitish Rana","options":["Shreyas Iyer","Nitish Rana","Sanju Samson","Rishabh Pant"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"Nitish Rana's journey from unknown Delhi cricketer to KKR's IPL captain is a classic zero-to-hero arc. The \"ridiculed → promoted → dominating → captaining\" trajectory fits Rana's improbable rise.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Not-good-enough"},{"lens":"The Oddity","form":"Form 9 (The Misdirection)","question_text":"It may sound like a medical condition, but \"fast-twitch fiber dominance with atypical elbow hyperextension\" — the physiological profile that scouts now actively look for in uncapped Indian bowlers — was first identified when an unknown Jammu pacer's action was analyzed on a smartphone app by a data analyst who had never played cricket in his life.","answer_text":"Umran Malik","options":["Navdeep Saini","Kartik Tyagi","Umran Malik","Mayank Yadav"],"backdoor_type":"Synonym Bridge","backdoor_explanation":"Umran Malik's pace was first noticed through data-driven scouting. The \"smartphone app\" analysis and \"Jammu\" location point directly to Malik, whose unique physiology allows him to bowl 150+ kph with a relatively slight frame.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Smartphone-app"},{"lens":"The Human Element","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Sleeping on the floor of a shared room with five other aspiring cricketers, surviving on one meal a day, and washing his only cricket jersey in a public tap every night so it would be clean for the next morning's trial — these were the conditions under which the uncapped batsman prepared for the tournament that would make him a crorepati before his twenty-first birthday.","answer_text":"Yashasvi Jaiswal","options":["Shubman Gill","Yashasvi Jaiswal","Devdutt Padikkal","Tilak Varma"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Jaiswal's story of homelessness in Mumbai — sleeping in a tent at Azad Maidan, selling pani puri, and washing his jersey at public taps — is the most powerful zero-to-hero story in cricket. Every detail here aligns with his documented early struggles.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"One-meal"},{"lens":"Behind the Scenes","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"What happens when a franchise's head scout secretly funds a 16-year-old's training for two years using his own salary, hiding the arrangement from the franchise's management because the official scouting budget had been exhausted? The teenager becomes the Emerging Player of the Season, and the scout gets a promotion — but only after the CEO discovered the arrangement through a leaked WhatsApp message.","answer_text":"Yashasvi Jaiswal","options":["Ruturaj Gaikwad",null,"Yashasvi Jaiswal","Riyan Parag"],"backdoor_type":"Category Elimination","backdoor_explanation":"This is Jaiswal's story — a Rajasthan Royals scout (or Mumbai cricket figure) quietly supporting his training. The \"Emerging Player\" award and the clandestine funding arrangement mirrors real stories of how uncapped talent was secretly nurtured before IPL contracts.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Scout"},{"lens":"Numbers & Scale","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"The crack of a tennis ball hitting a plywood board — the sound that echoed through a thousand gullies, a hundred maidans, and eventually one IPL stadium when the final of the tennis-ball tournament that discovered this uncapped star was live-streamed on YouTube and watched by 800,000 people, more than some international matches.","answer_text":"Rinku Singh","options":["Suryakumar Yadav","Rinku Singh","Nitish Rana","Priyam Garg"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Rinku Singh's tennis-ball cricket origins are legendary. The \"800,000 watching a tennis-ball tournament\" captures how the line between street cricket and professional scouting has blurred for the IPL generation.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Plywood"},{"lens":"The Rivalry","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Persistent, indestructible, and utterly unfazed by reputations, the uncapped finisher from Madhya Pradesh developed a trademark of specifically targeting the tournament's most expensive bowlers — he compiled a career strike rate above 190 against bowlers who earned more in a single season than he had earned in his entire life.","answer_text":"Rajat Patidar","options":["Jitesh Sharma","Rahul Tewatia","Rajat Patidar","Shahrukh Khan"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Patidar's ability to dominate premium bowlers — especially in the 2022 playoffs — defined his emergence. The \"targeting expensive bowlers\" trait captures the chip-on-the-shoulder mentality of uncapped sensations.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"190"},{"lens":"The Legacy","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Pioneering the template for the modern uncapped IPL discovery, the left-arm quick from a village whose name most Indians can't pronounce demonstrated that geography is irrelevant in the age of smartphone scouting — his success triggered a franchise arms race to deploy full-time scouts to every district-level tennis-ball tournament in India.","answer_text":"T. Natarajan","options":["Arshdeep Singh","T. Natarajan","Chetan Sakariya","Khaleel Ahmed"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Natarajan's rise from Chinnappampatti village to IPL star revolutionized scouting. The \"smartphone scouting\" and \"franchise arms race for district-level talent\" directly references how his story changed talent identification in Indian cricket.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Geography"},{"lens":"The Connection","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Every time I bowl, I think of the 300 rupees my father borrowed to buy my first pair of shoes\" — that line, delivered during a post-match interview after being named Man of the Match on debut, trended on social media for four consecutive days and was read aloud in the Indian Parliament by a member who used it to argue for increased sports funding in rural areas.","answer_text":"Chetan Sakariya","options":["Arshdeep Singh","Chetan Sakariya","Ravi Bishnoi","Avesh Khan"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Sakariya's emotional interviews about his family's financial struggles — particularly his father who was a tempo driver — made national news. The \"read in Parliament\" detail is a creative dramatization of how Sakariya's story resonated at the highest levels.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Parliament"}]$json$::jsonb,
